# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edmonds-karp-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In graph theory, a **flow network** (also known as a **transportation network**) is a directed graph where each edge has a **capacity** and each edge receives a flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The amount of flow on an edge cannot exceed the capacity of the edge.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Often in operations research, a directed graph is called a **network**, the vertices are called **nodes** and the edges are called **arcs**.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A flow must satisfy the restriction that the amount of flow into a node equals the amount of flow out of it, unless it is a **source**, which has only outgoing flow, or **sink**, which has only incoming flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A flow network can be used to model traffic in a computer network, circulation with demands, fluids in pipes, currents in an electrical circuit, or anything similar in which something travels through a network of nodes.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] As such, efficient algorithms for solving network flows can also be applied to solve problems that can be reduced to a flow network, including survey design, airline scheduling, image segmentation, and the matching problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A **network** is a directed graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with a non-negative **capacity** function *c* for each edge, and without multiple arcs (i.e. edges with the same source and target nodes).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Without loss of generality, we may assume that if (*u*, *v*) ∈ *E*, then (*v*, *u*) is also a member of E.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] If two nodes in G are distinguished – one as the source s and the other as the sink t – then (*G*, *c*, *s*, *t*) is called a **flow network**.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In flow networks, the source s is deficient, and the sink t is active.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Pseudo-flows, feasible flows, and pre-flows are all examples of flow functions.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The **value** |*f*| of a feasible flow f for a network, is the net flow into the sink t of the flow network, that is: |*f*| = *x**f* (*t*).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Note, the flow value in a network is also equal to the total outgoing flow of source s, that is: |*f*| = −*x**f* (*s*).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Also, if we define *A* as a set of nodes in *G* such that *s* ∈ *A* and *t* ∉ *A*, the flow value is equal to the total net flow going out of A (i.e. |*f*| = *f* out(*A*) − *f* in(*A*)).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The flow value in a network is the total amount of flow from s to t.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Flow decomposition is a process of breaking down a given flow into a collection of path flows and cycle flows.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Every flow through a network can be decomposed into one or more paths and corresponding quantities, such that each edge in the flow equals the sum of all quantities of paths that pass through it.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Flow decomposition is a powerful tool in optimization problems to maximize or minimize specific flow parameters.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] We do not use multiple arcs within a network because we can combine those arcs into a single arc.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Along with the other constraints, the skew symmetry constraint must be remembered during this step to maintain the direction of the original pseudo-flow arc.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Adding flow to an arc is the same as adding an arc with the capacity of zero.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The **residual capacity** of an arc e with respect to a pseudo-flow f is denoted *c**f*, and it is the difference between the arc's capacity and its flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] From this we can construct a **residual network**, denoted *G**f* (*V*, *E**f*), with a capacity function *c**f* which models the amount of *available* capacity on the set of arcs in *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] More specifically, capacity function *c**f* of each arc (*u*, *v*) in the residual network represents the amount of flow which can be transferred from u to v given the current state of the flow within the network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] This concept is used in Ford–Fulkerson algorithm which computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Note that there can be an unsaturated path (a path with available capacity) from u to v in the residual network, even though there is no such path from u to v in the original network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Since flows in opposite directions cancel out, *decreasing* the flow from v to u is the same as *increasing* the flow from u to v.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] More simply, an augmenting path is an available flow path from the source to the sink.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A network is at maximum flow if and only if there is no augmenting path in the residual network *G**f*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The **bottleneck** is the minimum residual capacity of all the edges in a given augmenting path.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] See example explained in the "Example" section of this article.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The flow network is at maximum flow if and only if it has a bottleneck with a value equal to zero.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] If any augmenting path exists, its bottleneck weight will be greater than 0.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In other words, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then there is an augmenting path from the source to the sink.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] However, we know that if there is any augmenting path, then the network is not at maximum flow, which in turn means that, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then the network is not at maximum flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The term "augmenting the flow" for an augmenting path means updating the flow f of each arc in this augmenting path to equal the capacity *c* of the bottleneck.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Augmenting the flow corresponds to pushing additional flow along the augmenting path until there is no remaining available residual capacity in the bottleneck.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Sometimes, when modeling a network with more than one source, a **supersource** is introduced to the graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] This consists of a vertex connected to each of the sources with edges of infinite capacity, so as to act as a global source.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A similar construct for sinks is called a **supersink**.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In Figure 1 you see a flow network with source labeled s, sink t, and four additional nodes.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The flow and capacity is denoted $f/c$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Notice how the network upholds the capacity constraint and flow conservation constraint.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The total amount of flow from s to t is 5, which can be easily seen from the fact that the total outgoing flow from s is 5, which is also the incoming flow to t.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] By the skew symmetry constraint, from c to a is -2 because the flow from a to c is 2.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In Figure 2 you see the residual network for the same given flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Notice how there is positive residual capacity on some edges where the original capacity is zero in Figure 1, for example for the edge $(d,c)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] There is available capacity along the paths $(s,a,c,t)$ , $(s,a,b,d,t)$ and $(s,a,b,d,c,t)$ , which are then the augmenting paths.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Picture a series of water pipes, fitting into a network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Each pipe is of a certain diameter, so it can only maintain a flow of a certain amount of water.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Anywhere that pipes meet, the total amount of water coming into that junction must be equal to the amount going out, otherwise we would quickly run out of water, or we would have a buildup of water.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] We have a water inlet, which is the source, and an outlet, the sink.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] A flow would then be one possible way for water to get from source to sink so that the total amount of water coming out of the outlet is consistent.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Intuitively, the total flow of a network is the rate at which water comes out of the outlet.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Flows can pertain to people or material over transportation networks, or to electricity over electrical distribution systems.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] For any such physical network, the flow coming into any intermediate node needs to equal the flow going out of that node.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] This conservation constraint is equivalent to Kirchhoff's current law.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Flow networks also find applications in ecology: flow networks arise naturally when considering the flow of nutrients and energy between different organisms in a food web.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The mathematical problems associated with such networks are quite different from those that arise in networks of fluid or traffic flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The field of ecosystem network analysis, developed by Robert Ulanowicz and others, involves using concepts from information theory and thermodynamics to study the evolution of these networks over time.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The simplest and most common problem using flow networks is to find what is called the maximum flow, which provides the largest possible total flow from the source to the sink in a given graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] There are many other problems which can be solved using max flow algorithms, if they are appropriately modeled as flow networks, such as bipartite matching, the assignment problem and the transportation problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Maximum flow problems can be solved in polynomial time with various algorithms (see table).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The max-flow min-cut theorem states that finding a maximal network flow is equivalent to finding a cut of minimum capacity that separates the source and the sink, where a cut is the division of vertices such that the source is in one division and the sink is in another.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In a multi-commodity flow problem, you have multiple sources and sinks, and various "commodities" which are to flow from a given source to a given sink.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] This could be for example various goods that are produced at various factories, and are to be delivered to various given customers through the *same* transportation network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In a minimum cost flow problem, each edge $u,v$ has a given cost $k(u,v)$ , and the cost of sending the flow $f(u,v)$ across the edge is $f(u,v)\cdot k(u,v)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The objective is to send a given amount of flow from the source to the sink, at the lowest possible price.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In a circulation problem, you have a lower bound $\ell (u,v)$ on the edges, in addition to the upper bound $c(u,v)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] Often, flow conservation holds for *all* nodes in a circulation problem, and there is a connection from the sink back to the source.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In this way, you can dictate the total flow with $\ell (t,s)$ and $c(t,s)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] The flow *circulates* through the network, hence the name of the problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In a **network with gains** or **generalized network** each edge has a **gain**, a real number (not zero) such that, if the edge has gain *g*, and an amount *x* flows into the edge at its tail, then an amount *gx* flows out at the head.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] In a **source localization problem**, an algorithm tries to identify the most likely source node of information diffusion through a partially observed network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/augmenting-path] This can be done in linear time for trees and cubic time for arbitrary networks and has applications ranging from tracking mobile phone users to identifying the originating source of disease outbreaks.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] For example, in a chess endgame, a chess engine may build the game tree from the current position by applying all possible moves and use breadth-first search to find a winning position for White.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Implicit trees (such as game trees or other problem-solving trees) may be of infinite size; breadth-first search is guaranteed to find a solution node if one exists.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In contrast, (plain) depth-first search (DFS), which explores the node branch as far as possible before backtracking and expanding other nodes, may get lost in an infinite branch and never make it to the solution node.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Iterative deepening depth-first search avoids the latter drawback at the price of exploring the tree's top parts over and over again.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] On the other hand, both depth-first algorithms typically require far less extra memory than breadth-first search.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search can be generalized to both undirected graphs and directed graphs with a given start node (sometimes referred to as a 'search key').
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In state space search in artificial intelligence, repeated searches of vertices are often allowed, while in theoretical analysis of algorithms based on breadth-first search, precautions are typically taken to prevent repetitions.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] BFS and its application in finding connected components of graphs were invented in 1945 by Konrad Zuse, in his (rejected) Ph.D. thesis on the Plankalkül programming language, but this was not published until 1972.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Moore, who used it to find the shortest path out of a maze, and later developed by C.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Lee into a wire routing algorithm (published in 1961).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The below pseudocode finds the shortest path from a given root vertex to all other vertices in the graph using BFS.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] 2. it checks whether a vertex has been explored before enqueueing the vertex rather than delaying this check until the vertex is dequeued from the queue.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of this breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterative depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a breadth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The queue Q contains the frontier along which the algorithm is currently searching.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Nodes can be labelled as explored by storing them in a set, or by an attribute on each node, depending on the implementation.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The *parent* attribute of each node is useful for accessing the nodes in a shortest path, for example by backtracking from the destination node up to the starting node, once the BFS has been run, and the predecessors nodes have been set.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search produces a *breadth-first tree*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The diagrams on the right show the breadth-first tree obtained by running a BFS on an example graph of German cities (upper diagram) starting from *Frankfurt*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] The time complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|+|E|)$ , as every vertex and every edge will be explored in the worst case. $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ is the number of edges in the graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Note that $O(|E|)$ may vary between $O(1)$ and $O(|V|^{2})$ , depending on how sparse the input graph is.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] When the number of vertices in the graph is known ahead of time, and additional data structures are used to determine which vertices have already been added to the queue, the space complexity can be expressed as $O(|V|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] This is in addition to the space required for the graph itself, which may vary depending on the graph representation used by an implementation of the algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In the analysis of algorithms, the input to breadth-first search is assumed to be a finite graph, represented as an adjacency list, adjacency matrix, or similar representation.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] However, in the application of graph traversal methods in artificial intelligence the input may be an implicit representation of an infinite graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] In this context, a search method is described as being complete if it is guaranteed to find a goal state if one exists.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Breadth-first search is complete, but depth-first search is not.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] When applied to infinite graphs represented implicitly, breadth-first search will eventually find the goal state, but depth first search may get lost in parts of the graph that have no goal state and never return.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] An enumeration of the vertices of a graph is said to be a BFS ordering if it is a possible output of the application of BFS to this graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a graph with n vertices.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Recall that $N(v)$ is the set of neighbors of v .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Let $\sigma =(v_{1},\dots ,v_{m})$ be a list of distinct elements of V , for $v\in V\setminus \{v_{1},\dots ,v_{m}\}$ , let $\nu _{\sigma }(v)$ be the least i such that $v_{i}$ is a neighbor of v , if such a i exists, and be $\infty$ otherwise.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Let $\sigma =(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be an enumeration of the vertices of V .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/breadth-first-search] Equivalently, $\sigma$ is a BFS ordering if, for all $1\leq i<j<k\leq n$ with $v_{i}\in N(v_{k})\setminus N(v_{j})$ , there exists a neighbor $v_{m}$ of $v_{j}$ such that $m<i$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] In computer science, the **Edmonds–Karp algorithm** is an implementation of the Ford–Fulkerson method for computing the maximum flow in a flow network in $O(|V||E|^{2})$ time.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The algorithm was first published by Yefim Dinitz in 1970, and independently published by Jack Edmonds and Richard Karp in 1972.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Dinitz's algorithm includes additional techniques that reduce the running time to $O(|V|^{2}|E|)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The algorithm is identical to the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm, except that the search order when finding the augmenting path is defined.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The path found must be a shortest path that has available capacity.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] This can be found by a breadth-first search, where we apply a weight of 1 to each edge.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Another property of this algorithm is that the length of the shortest augmenting path increases monotonically.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The proof first establishes that distance of the shortest path from the source node s to any non-sink node v in a residual flow network increases monotonically after each augmenting iteration (Lemma 1, proven below).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Then, it shows that each of the $|E|$ edges can be critical at most ${\frac {|V|}{2}}$ times for the duration of the algorithm, giving an upper-bound of $O\left({\frac {|V||E|}{2}}\right)=O(|V||E|)$ augmenting iterations.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Since each iteration takes $O(|E|)$ time (bounded by the time for finding the shortest path using Breadth-First-Search), the total running time of Edmonds-Karp is $O(|V||E|^{2})$ as required.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] To prove Lemma 1, one can use proof by contradiction by assuming that there is an augmenting iteration that causes the shortest path distance from s to v to *decrease*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Let f be the flow before such an augmentation and $f'$ be the flow after.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Denote the minimum distance in a residual flow network ⁠ $G_{f}$ ⁠ from nodes $u,v$ as $\delta _{f}(u,v)$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] One can derive a contradiction by showing that $\delta _{f}(s,v)\leq \delta _{f'}(s,v)$ , meaning that the shortest path distance between source node s and non-sink node v did not in fact decrease.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] In the pairs $f/c$ written on the edges, f is the current flow, and c is the capacity.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The residual capacity from u to v is $c_{f}(u,v)=c(u,v)-f(u,v)$ , the total capacity, minus the flow that is already used.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] If the net flow from u to v is negative, it *contributes* to the residual capacity.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] Notice how the length of the augmenting path found by the algorithm (in red) never decreases.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The paths found are the shortest possible.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/edmonds-karp-algorithm] The flow found is equal to the capacity across the minimum cut in the graph separating the source and the sink.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The **Ford–Fulkerson method** or **Ford–Fulkerson algorithm** (**FFA**) is a greedy algorithm that computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] It is sometimes called a "method" instead of an "algorithm" as the approach to finding augmenting paths in a residual graph is not fully specified or it is specified in several implementations with different running times.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The name "Ford–Fulkerson" is often also used for the Edmonds–Karp algorithm, which is a fully defined implementation of the Ford–Fulkerson method.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The idea behind the algorithm is as follows: as long as there is a path from the source (start node) to the sink (end node), with available capacity on all edges in the path, we send flow along one of the paths.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] A path with available capacity is called an augmenting path.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Let $G(V,E)$ be a graph, and for each edge from u to v, let $c(u,v)$ be the capacity and $f(u,v)$ be the flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] We want to find the maximum flow from the source s to the sink t.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] This means that the flow through the network is a *legal flow* after each round in the algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] We define the **residual network** $G_{f}(V,E_{f})$ to be the network with capacity $c_{f}(u,v)=c(u,v)-f(u,v)$ and no flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Notice that it can happen that a flow from v to u is allowed in the residual network, though disallowed in the original network: if $f(u,v)>0$ and $c(v,u)=0$ then $c_{f}(v,u)=c(v,u)-f(v,u)=f(u,v)>0$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The path in step 2 can be found with, for example, breadth-first search (BFS) or depth-first search in $G_{f}(V,E_{f})$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The former is known as the Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] When no more paths in step 2 can be found, s will not be able to reach t in the residual network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] If S is the set of nodes reachable by s in the residual network, then the total capacity in the original network of edges from S to the remainder of V is on the one hand equal to the total flow we found from s to t, and on the other hand serves as an upper bound for all such flows.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] This proves that the flow we found is maximal.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] If the graph $G(V,E)$ has multiple sources and sinks, we act as follows: Suppose that $T=\{t\mid t{\text{ is a sink}}\}$ and $S=\{s\mid s{\text{ is a source}}\}$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Then apply the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Also, if a node u has capacity constraint $d_{u}$ , we replace this node with two nodes $u_{\mathrm {in} },u_{\mathrm {out} }$ , and an edge $(u_{\mathrm {in} },u_{\mathrm {out} })$ , with capacity $c(u_{\mathrm {in} },u_{\mathrm {out} })=d_{u}$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] We can then apply the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] By adding the flow augmenting path to the flow already established in the graph, the maximum flow will be reached when no more flow augmenting paths can be found in the graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] However, there is no certainty that this situation will ever be reached, so the best that can be guaranteed is that the answer will be correct if the algorithm terminates.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] In the case that the algorithm does not terminate, the flow might not converge towards the maximum flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] However, this situation only occurs with irrational flow values.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] When the capacities are integers, the runtime of Ford–Fulkerson is bounded by $O(Ef)$ (see big O notation), where E is the number of edges in the graph and f is the maximum flow in the graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] This is because each augmenting path can be found in $O(E)$ time and increases the flow by an integer amount of at least 1 , with the upper bound f .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] A variation of the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm with guaranteed termination and a runtime independent of the maximum flow value is the Edmonds–Karp algorithm, which runs in $O(VE^{2})$ time.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The following example shows the first steps of Ford–Fulkerson in a flow network with 4 nodes, source A and sink D .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] This example shows the worst-case behaviour of the algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] In each step, only a flow of 1 is sent across the network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] If breadth-first-search were used instead, only two steps would be needed.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Consider the flow network shown on the right, with source s , sink t , capacities of edges $e_{1}=1$ , $e_{2}=r=({\sqrt {5}}-1)/2$ and $e_{3}=1$ , and the capacity of all other edges some integer $M\geq 2$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] The constant r was chosen so, that $r^{2}=1-r$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Note that after step 1 as well as after step 5, the residual capacities of edges $e_{1}$ , $e_{2}$ and $e_{3}$ are in the form $r^{n}$ , $r^{n+1}$ and 0 , respectively, for some $n\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] This means that we can use augmenting paths $p_{1}$ , $p_{2}$ , $p_{1}$ and $p_{3}$ infinitely many times and residual capacities of these edges will always be in the same form.
