[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm never terminates and the flow does not converge to the maximum flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/ford-fulkerson-algorithm] Another non-terminating example based on the Euclidean algorithm is given by Backman & Huynh (2018), where they also show that the worst case running-time of the Ford-Fulkerson algorithm on a network $G(V,E)$ in ordinal numbers is $\omega ^{\Theta (|E|)}$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In optimization theory, **maximum flow problems** involve finding a feasible flow through a flow network that obtains the maximum possible flow rate.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem can be seen as a special case of more complex network flow problems, such as the circulation problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum value of an s-t flow (i.e., flow from source s to sink t) is equal to the minimum capacity of an s-t cut (i.e., cut severing s from t) in the network, as stated in the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The maximum flow problem was first formulated in 1954 by T.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Ross as a simplified model of Soviet railway traffic flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Fulkerson created the first known algorithm, the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In their 1955 paper, Ford and Fulkerson wrote that the problem of Harris and Ross is formulated as follows (see p.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] where [11] refers to the 1955 secret report *Fundamentals of a Method for Evaluating Rail net Capacities* by Harris and Ross (see p.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The algorithms of Sherman and Kelner, Lee, Orecchia and Sidford, respectively, find an approximately optimal maximum flow but only work in undirected graphs.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Orlin published a paper describing an $O(|V||E|)$ algorithm.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Liu, Richard Peng, Maximilian Probst Gutenberg, and Sushant Sachdeva published an almost-linear time algorithm running in $O(|E|^{1+o(1)})$ for the minimum-cost flow problem of which the maximum flow problem is a particular case.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] For the single-source shortest path (SSSP) problem with negative weights – another particular case of a minimum-cost flow problem – an algorithm running in almost-linear time has also been reported.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Both algorithms were deemed best papers at the 2022 Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Note that several maximum flows may exist, and if arbitrary real (or even arbitrary rational) values of flow are permitted (instead of just integers), there is either exactly one maximum flow, or infinitely many, since there are infinitely many linear combinations of the base maximum flows.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, if we send x units of flow on edge u in one maximum flow, and $y>x$ units of flow on u in another maximum flow, then for each $\Delta \in [0,y-x]$ we can send $x+\Delta$ units on u and route the flow on remaining edges accordingly, to obtain another maximum flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If flow values can be any real or rational numbers, then there are infinitely many such $\Delta$ values for each pair $x,y$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The following tables show the historical development of algorithms for solving the maximum flow problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Many of the listed publications include similar tables comparing their results to earlier works.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A strongly-polynomial time algorithm has polynomial time bounds that depend only on the number of inputs, but do not depend on the magnitude of these numbers.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the inputs are the vertices (numbered below as V ) and edges (numbered as E ).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The complexity of each algorithm is stated using big O notation.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In parallel to the development of strongly-polynomial flow algorithms, there has been a long line of pseudo-polynomial and weakly polynomial time bounds, whose running time depends on the magnitude of the input capacities.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Here, the value U refers to the largest edge capacity after rescaling all capacities to integer values.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If each edge in a flow network has integral capacity, then there exists an integral maximal flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The claim is not only that the value of the flow is an integer, which follows directly from the max-flow min-cut theorem, but that the flow on *every edge* is integral.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] This is crucial for many combinatorial applications (see below), where the flow across an edge may encode whether the item corresponding to that edge is to be included in the set sought or not.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a network $N=(V,E)$ with a set of sources $S=\{s_{1},\ldots ,s_{n}\}$ and a set of sinks $T=\{t_{1},\ldots ,t_{m}\}$ instead of only one source and one sink, we are to find the maximum flow across N .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We can transform the multi-source multi-sink problem into a maximum flow problem by adding a *consolidated source* connecting to each vertex in S and a *consolidated sink*connected by each vertex in T (also known as *supersource* and *supersink*) with infinite capacity on each edge (See Fig.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a bipartite graph $G=(X\cup Y,E)$ , we are to find a maximum cardinality matching in G , that is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow in N is equal to the size of the maximum matching in G , and a maximum cardinality matching can be found by taking those edges that have flow 1 in an integral max-flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed acyclic graph $G=(V,E)$ , we are to find the minimum number of vertex-disjoint paths to cover each vertex in V .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then it can be shown that $G'$ has a matching M of size m if and only if G has a vertex-disjoint path cover C containing m edges and $n-m$ paths, where n is the number of vertices in G .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, the problem can be solved by finding the maximum cardinality matching in $G'$ instead.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Assume we have found a matching M of $G'$ , and constructed the cover C from it.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Intuitively, if two vertices $u_{\mathrm {out} },v_{\mathrm {in} }$ are matched in M , then the edge $(u,v)$ is contained in C .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Similarly for each vertex $v_{\textrm {in}}$ in $G'$ – if it is matched, there is a single incoming edge into v in C ; otherwise v has no incoming edges in C .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Thus no vertex has two incoming or two outgoing edges in C , which means all paths in C are vertex-disjoint.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To show that the cover C has size $n-m$ , we start with an empty cover and build it incrementally.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To add a vertex u to the cover, we can either add it to an existing path, or create a new path of length zero starting at that vertex.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The former case is applicable whenever either $(u,v)\in E$ and some path in the cover starts at v , or $(v,u)\in E$ and some path ends at v .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the former case, the total number of edges in the cover is increased by 1 and the number of paths stays the same; in the latter case the number of paths is increased and the number of edges stays the same.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] It is now clear that after covering all n vertices, the sum of the number of paths and edges in the cover is n .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Therefore, if the number of edges in the cover is m , the number of paths is $n-m$ .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, the amount of flow passing through a vertex cannot exceed its capacity.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To find the maximum flow across N , we can transform the problem into the maximum flow problem in the original sense by expanding N .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] First, each $v\in V$ is replaced by $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ , where $v_{\text{in}}$ is connected by edges going into v and $v_{\text{out}}$ is connected to edges coming out from v , then assign capacity $c(v)$ to the edge connecting $v_{\text{in}}$ and $v_{\text{out}}$ (see Fig.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this expanded network, the vertex capacity constraint is removed and therefore the problem can be treated as the original maximum flow problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed graph $G=(V,E)$ and two vertices s and t , we are to find the maximum number of paths from s to t .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The paths must be independent, i.e., vertex-disjoint (except for s and t ).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We can construct a network $N=(V,E)$ from G with vertex capacities, where the capacities of all vertices and all edges are 1 .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow is equal to the maximum number of independent paths from s to t .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In addition to the paths being edge-disjoint and/or vertex disjoint, the paths also have a length constraint: we count only paths whose length is exactly k , or at most k .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Most variants of this problem are NP-complete, except for small values of k .
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A **closure** of a directed graph is a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The **closure problem** is the task of finding the maximum-weight or minimum-weight closure in a vertex-weighted directed graph.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the baseball elimination problem there are *n* teams competing in a league.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] At a specific stage of the league season, *w**i* is the number of wins and *r**i* is the number of games left to play for team *i* and *r*ij is the number of games left against team *j*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A team is eliminated if it has no chance to finish the season in the first place.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The task of the baseball elimination problem is to determine which teams are eliminated at each point during the season.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Schwartz proposed a method which reduces this problem to maximum network flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this method a network is created to determine whether team *k* is eliminated.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* being the source and the sink respectively.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] One adds a game node*ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with *i* < *j* to *V*, and connects each of them from *s* by an edge with capacity *r**ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with two team nodes *i* and *j* to ensure one of them wins.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] One does not need to restrict the flow value on these edges.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Finally, edges are made from team node *i* to the sink node *t* and the capacity of *w**k* + *r**k* – *w**i* is set to prevent team *i* from winning more than *w**k* + *r**k*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In this method it is claimed team *k* is not eliminated if and only if a flow value of size *r*(*S* − {*k*}) exists in network *G*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned article it is proved that this flow value is the maximum flow value from *s* to *t*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the airline industry a major problem is the scheduling of the flight crews.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The airline scheduling problem can be considered as an application of extended maximum network flow.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The input of this problem is a set of flights *F* which contains the information about where and when each flight departs and arrives.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In one version of airline scheduling the goal is to produce a feasible schedule with at most *k* crews.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To solve this problem one uses a variation of the circulation problem called bounded circulation which is the generalization of network flow problems, with the added constraint of a lower bound on edge flows.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* as the source and the sink nodes.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] For the source and destination of every flight *i*, one adds two nodes to *V*, node *s**i* as the source and node *d**i* as the destination node of flight *i*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *t*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [1, 1] between each pair of *s**i* and *d**i*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *s**j*, if source *s**j* is reachable with a reasonable amount of time and cost from the destination of flight *i*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, ∞] between *s* and *t*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned method, it is claimed and proved that finding a flow value of *k* in *G* between *s* and *t* is equal to finding a feasible schedule for flight set *F* with at most *k* crews.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Another version of airline scheduling is finding the minimum needed crews to perform all the flights.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] To find an answer to this problem, a bipartite graph *G'* = (*A* ∪ *B*, *E*) is created where each flight has a copy in set *A* and set *B*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If the same plane can perform flight *j* after flight *i*, *i*∈*A* is connected to *j*∈*B*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] A matching in G' induces a schedule for *F* and obviously maximum bipartite matching in this graph produces an airline schedule with minimum number of crews.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] As it is mentioned in the Application part of this article, the maximum cardinality bipartite matching is an application of maximum flow problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] There are some factories that produce goods and some villages where the goods have to be delivered.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] They are connected by a networks of roads with each road having a capacity c for maximum goods that can flow through it.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The problem is to find if there is a circulation that satisfies the demand.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] This problem can be transformed into a maximum-flow problem.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Add a sink node t and add edges from all villages vi to t with capacity di where di is the demand rate of village vi.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be this new network.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] If there exists a circulation, looking at the max-flow solution would give the answer as to how much goods have to be sent on a particular road for satisfying the demands.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] The problem can be extended by adding a lower bound on the flow on some edges.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] In their book, Kleinberg and Tardos present an algorithm for segmenting an image.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] They present an algorithm to find the background and the foreground in an image.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Indeed, for pixels in *A* (considered as the foreground), we gain *ai*; for all pixels in *B* (considered as the background), we gain *bi*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] On the border, between two adjacent pixels *i* and *j*, we loose *pij*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We now construct the network whose nodes are the pixel, plus a source and a sink, see Figure on the right.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the source to pixel *i* by an edge of weight *ai*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the pixel *i* to the sink by an edge of weight *bi*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] We connect pixel *i* to pixel *j* with weight *pij*.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] Now, it remains to compute a minimum cut in that network (or equivalently a maximum flow).
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] With negative constraints, the problem becomes strongly NP-hard even for simple networks.
[src:edmonds-karp-algorithm/maximum-flow-problem] With positive constraints, the problem is polynomial if fractional flows are allowed, but may be strongly NP-hard when the flows must be integral.
